# thrift (Cursor port) — workspace rules

This workspace has the `harness-thrift-cursor` kit installed. Cursor has
no programmatic hooks and no exposed prompt cache, so the cost-conscious
workflow lives entirely in this rule. The planner reads it on every turn.

## Origin

Source-of-truth design: `plugins/harness-thrift/skills/thrift/SKILL.md`
(Claude Code). Per-platform spec:
`docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-18-harness-thrift-per-platform-decomposition.md`
(Cursor section). Local skill: `plugins/harness-thrift-cursor/skills/thrift-cursor/SKILL.md`.

## Cost-conscious rules

### 1. Coerce large tool outputs to context-mode

If context-mode-cursor is installed (check `.cursor/mcp.json` for a
`context-mode` MCP entry), prefer its `ctx_execute` and
`ctx_execute_file` tools over `run_shell_command` for any command
expected to produce more than `{{coerceBashWhenOutputExceeds}}` lines
of output, or any file Read above `{{coerceReadWhenOutputExceeds}}`
lines. The MCP tools keep raw output in a sandbox and return only the
summary you need, which keeps the chat window short.

If context-mode-cursor is **not** installed, this clause is a no-op —
proceed with the default tool, but be aware large outputs eat your
context budget.

### 2. Suggest summarisation at thresholds

After roughly `{{everyNTurns}}` of your turns, OR whenever you have
produced ~`{{everyMTokensOutput}}` output tokens (estimate from your
own reply lengths — Cursor does not surface exact counts), propose a
summarisation pass to the user:

> "This chat is getting long. Per the thrift rule, I can write a
> one-page summary of the work so far to
> `.agent-skill/reports/thrift/cursor-summary-<date>-<HHMM>.md` so you can start a
> fresh chat with that file in context. Proceed?"

When the user accepts:
1. Keep the last 6 turns verbatim in the summary as quoted blocks.
2. For earlier turns, produce a one-line bullet per turn with the
   action taken + the file path(s) touched.
3. List open TODOs.
4. Write the file. Tell the user where it is.

### 3. End-of-session recap

Before the user ends a long session (heuristic: ≥30 minutes wall clock
or ≥`{{everyNTurns}}` turns), proactively offer to write an end-of-session
recap to `.agent-skill/reports/thrift/cursor-recap-<date>.md`. The recap covers:

- What was attempted.
- Files touched (paths only, with one-line descriptions).
- What worked, what didn't.
- Outstanding TODOs / unresolved questions.

This recap replaces the Claude Code skill's quantified token-cost audit
report — Cursor does not surface token counts, so we deliver a narrative
recap instead.

### 4. What this rule does NOT do

- **No cache priming.** Cursor exposes no prompt-cache surface; the
  Claude Code skill's Phase 4 is removed entirely.
- **No automatic enforcement.** This is an advisory rule. Cursor's
  planner reads it but the user can ignore the suggestions at any time.
- **No state file.** `.thrift-state.json` is not produced. Metrics that
  would have lived there (turn counts, token totals, coercion telemetry,
  cache hit rate) are not collected.

## Configuration

Edit `.thrift.json` at the workspace root to tune thresholds. The rule
re-reads them on the next chat turn (rules are reloaded per turn).

## Source-of-truth

For the full design rationale, see
`plugins/harness-thrift/skills/thrift/SKILL.md`. Cursor's port adapts
the contract but preserves the intent: keep raw output off the
conversation surface, summarise long sessions, and write a recap at
session end.
